This paper discusses the use of fog computing and osmotic computing to manage service heterogeneity, which involves the allocation of computational resources based on the characteristics of different services. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI), Systems and Control (cs.SY), Software Engineering (cs.SE), and Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE). However, given the focus on resource allocation and management, Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) is the most likely sub-category, followed by Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Systems and Control (cs.SY).
